item.label: Cerebral lobe, Occipital
item.name: Cerebral lobes, occipital
item.description: The occipital lobe is the most posterior lobe of the cerebral hemispheres. It is clinically important because it includes the primary and association visual cortex.

item.label: Visual pathway
item.name: Visual pathway
item.description: The entire visual pathway begins in the retina and terminates in the calcarine cortex of the occipital lobe.  The components of the pathway are the optic nerve, optic chiasm, optic tract, lateral geniculate nucleus and optic radiations.

item.label: Optic radiation
item.name: Optic radiation
item.description: The Optic Radiation is AKA geniculocalcarine tract. It is a massive bundle of myelinated nerve fibers that originate in the lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus and terminate in the upper and lower banks of the calcarine sulcus in the occipital lobe. It travels through the sublenticular and retrolenticular portions of the posterior limb of the internal capsule.

item.label: Line of Gennari
item.name: Line of Gennari
item.description: The Line of Gennari is AKA the Stripe of Gennari.  It is a thin, white stripe in the primary visual cortex of the calcarine cortex. Visual cortex is often called striate cortex because of this line that is visible to the naked eye.

item.label: Medulla
item.name: Medulla
item.description: The medulla is AKA the medulla oblongata. The most caudal aspect of the brain stem, it is located between the pons and spinal cord. It contains structures vital to survival such as cardiovascular and respiratory centers, as well as many cranial nerve nuclei. The major ascending and descending tracts travel through it between the spinal cord and higher centers. It originates developmentally from the myelencephalon of the hindbrain.

item.label: Olivary complex
item.name: Olivary complex
item.description: The inferior olivary complex consists of the large inferior olivary nucleus (AKA the principal olivary nucleus) plus the dorsal and medial accessory olivary nuclei.  Together they are responsible for the large 'olive' on the lateral aspect of the medulla.  The output of this nuclear complex consists of 'climbing fibers' that project to the contralateral cerebellum.  The principal inferior olivary nucleus projects to the hemispheres of the cerebellum while the accessory nuclei project to the vermis and flocculus of the cerebellum.  Note that the superior olivary nucleus is NOT part of this nuclear complex, but rather is associated with the auditory pathway.

item.label: Inferior olivary nucleus
item.name: Inferior olivary nuclei
item.description: The inferior olivary nucleus is a large, convoluted, drawstring purse-like nucleus in the anterolateral medulla.  It receives multiple afferents from the spinal cord, red nucleus, cerebellum, etc. It projects to the contralateral cerebellum via olivocerebellar fibers that travel in the contralateral inferior cerebellar peduncle to terminate as climbing fibers in the cerebellum. Can be confused with the dentate nucleus in the cerebellum because of its similar appearance.

item.label: Accessory olivary nucleus
item.name: Accessory olivary nuclei
item.description: The inferior olivary complex consists of the large inferior olivary nucleus (AKA the principal olivary nucleus) plus the dorsal and medial accessory olivary nuclei.  Together they are responsible for the large 'olive' on the lateral aspect of the medulla.  The output of this nuclear complex consists of 'climbing fibers' that project to the contralateral cerebellum.  The principal inferior olivary nucleus projects to the hemispheres of the cerebellum while the accessory nuclei project to the vermis and flocculus of the cerebellum.  Note that the superior olivary nucleus is NOT part of this nuclear complex, but rather is associated with the auditory pathway.

item.label: Pyramid
item.name: Pyramids
item.description: The pyramid is a large fiber bundle located on the medial and ventral aspect of the medulla. It consists of corticospinal (and some corticobulbar) fibers that originate in the ipsilateral cerebral cortex (precentral gyrus and elsewhere). These upper motor neuron fibers terminate on lower motor neurons in the ventral horn of the spinal cord (corticospinal) and on cranial nerve motor neurons in the medulla (corticobulbar). Often referred to as the pyramidal tract.

item.label: Cerebellum
item.name: Cerebellum
item.description: The cerebellum is sometimes referred to as the 'small' brain.  It is located within the posterior fossa, superior to the brain stem. It consists of a finely convoluted cortical surface of folia, a central core of white matter (AKA medullary center) and four paired deep nuclei (dentate, emboliform, fastigial and globose) embedded within the white matter core. The cerebellum functions in the planning and coordination of movement.

item.label: Hemisphere
item.name: Hemispheres
item.description: The cerebellar hemispheres are the largest portion of the cerebellum located on either side of the midline vermis. They are functionally important relative to coordination of the limbs.

item.label: Flocculus
item.name: Flocculi
item.description: The flocculus is the hemispheric portion of the flocculonodular lobe of the cerebellum.  It is concerned with balance and equilibrium as well as movements of the eyes.

item.label: Vermis
item.name: Vermis
item.description: The vermis of the cerebellum is the most medial region, i.e. the narrow midline section associated with the anterior, posterior and flocculonodular lobes of the cerebellum.

item.label: Lingula
item.name: Lingula
item.description: The lingula is a small extension of cerebellar folia from the cerebellar vermis.  It is located on the superior surface of the superior medullary velum between the superior cerebellar peduncles.

item.label: Cerebellar peduncles
item.name: Cerebellum, peduncles
item.description: There are three pair of cerebellar peduncles that consist of nerve fibers connecting the cerebellum with the brainstem and elsewhere.  Included are the paired superior, middle and inferior cerebellar peduncles.

item.label: Superior
item.name: Superior
item.description: The superior cerebellar peduncle is the major efferent path from the cerebellum. It carries information from the deep cerebellar nuclei to the contralateral motor part of thalamus (VL and VA) and to the contralateral red nucleus of the midbrain. It decussates or crosses the midline within the caudal midbrain.  While this peduncle is primarily efferent relative to the cerebellum, it does contain a significant afferent pathway, the ventral or anterior spinocerebellar tract.

item.label: Middle
item.name: Middle
item.description: The middle cerebellar peduncle consists exclusively of pontocerebellar tract fibers that take their origin from pontine nuclei in the contralateral basilar pons. Thus, it carries afferent information to cerebellum from the contralateral cerebral cortex via the corticopontine to pontine nuclei to pontocerebellar tract.

item.label: Inferior
item.name: Inferior
item.description: The inferior cerebellar peduncle is AKA the restiform body. Located on the lateral aspect of the medulla, it includes multiple tracts afferent to the cerebellum including the uncrossed dorsal or posterior spinocerebellar, cuneocerebellar, vestibulocerebellar, reticulocerebellar and crossed olivocerebellar. It also includes some cerebellar output tracts such as those projecting to the reticular formation and the vestibular nuclei.

item.label: Ventricular system
item.name: Ventricular system
item.description: The ventricular system is a series of interconnected cerebrospinal-filled chambers within the cerebral hemispheres. Cerebrospinal fluid is formed in the choroid plexus located in the lateral, third and fourth ventricles.

item.label: Lateral ventricle, Posterior horn
item.name: Lateral ventricles Poster
item.description: The posterior horn of the lateral ventricle is AKA the occipital horn. This region of the lateral ventricle extends into the occipital lobe.

item.label: Fourth ventricle
item.name: Fourth ventricle
item.description: The fourth ventricle is a rhomboid-shaped space located superior to the pons and medulla. The roof of the fourth ventricle is formed by the inferior and superior medullary vela plus the cerebellum. Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) enters the fourth ventricle from the third ventricle via the cerebral aqueduct. CSF exits the fourth ventricle into the subarachnoid space via the medial foramen of Magendie, located in the roof of the fourth ventricle, and the two lateral foramina of Luschka, located at the most lateral aspect of the fourth ventricle, i.e. in the lateral recess of the fourth ventricle, bilaterally.  The choroid plexus is located in the roof of the fourth ventricle, beneath the inferior medullary velum.  The choroid plexus extends outside of the fourth ventricle through the foramina of Luschka, where it can be visualized in the subarachnoid space.

item.label: Superior medullary velum
item.name: Superior medullary velum
item.description: The superior medullary velum is a thin layer of white matter that stretched between the paired superior cerebellar peduncles.  Along with the superior cerebellar peduncles, it forms part of the roof of the fourth ventricle.
